model_response.meaning: to give a part of something to somebody
model_response.explanation: The word 'divide' in English generally means to separate or part something into equal parts or shares. The word 'share' in English generally means to give a part of something to somebody. Although 'divide' and 'share' can have this meaning, 'separate' does not. 'Separate' generally means to isolate or divide something into parts, but it doesn't necessarily imply giving a part to somebody. 'Split' can also have this meaning in certain contexts, but it's not as common as 'divide' or 'share'.
model_response.example: For example, 'I will divide the cake among my friends' or 'I will share the cake with my friends' implies giving a part of the cake to somebody, whereas 'I will separate the cake into two parts' doesn't necessarily mean giving a part to somebody.

However, 'separate' does not typically have this meaning, as it generally implies isolating or distinguishing something from others, rather than distributing it.
model_response.example: For example, 'I will divide the money among my friends', 'I will split the bill with my friends', or 'I will share the food with my friends' all imply distributing something, whereas 'I will separate the money into different accounts' does not necessarily mean distributing it among people.
